```

## Rules
- No `any` — use `unknown` and type-narrow, or proper generics
- No non-null assertions (`!`) unless the value is guaranteed by the DOM structure
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- Prefer `type` for union types and mapped types
- All `useEffect` dependencies must be exhaustive (ESLint enforces this)
- Event handlers typed: `React.MouseEvent<HTMLButtonElement>` not `any`
- CSS Module types: import `styles` from `"./Component.module.css"` — TS infers keys

## GSAP types
```ts
import { gsap } from "gsap";
import type { GSAPTween, GSAPTimeline } from "gsap";

// Store tween for cleanup:
const tween = useRef<GSAPTween | null>(null);
useEffect(() => () => { tween.current?.kill(); }, []);
```

## Three.js types
```ts
import type { Mesh, MeshStandardMaterial, Group } from "three";

const meshRef = useRef<Mesh>(null);
const groupRef = useRef<Group>(null);
```

## Null safety pattern
```ts
// Always guard refs before use:
if (!sectionRef.current || !headingRef.current) return;

// Or use optional chaining:
sectionRef.current?.classList.add("visible");
```

## Avoid these patterns
```ts
// ❌ Bad
const el = document.querySelector(".hero") as HTMLElement;
gsap.to(el, { x: 100 }); // bypasses null check

// ✅ Good
const el = document.querySelector<HTMLElement>(".hero");
if (!el) return;
gsap.to(el, { x: 100 });
```
